    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup centers around the high-efficiency potential of **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (76.05) and **Jonathan Aranda** (68.94). **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** is our clear anchor; facing Cameron, he benefits from a positive SP skill adjustment and a favorable order slot, making him the safest bet for production. Meanwhile, **Jonathan Aranda** offers the most surprising value of the day. Despite park factors working against him, the matchup against Assad\u2019s 4.83 xERA provides a significant +19% boost to his efficiency, cementing his role as our primary 1B. We are also leaning heavily into **Yainer Diaz** (66.01) against Freeland; the combination of a high-run-environment park and the matchup against a left-handed arm provides the necessary upside to justify his spot in the UTIL slot, even with his lower spot in the batting order.\n\nOur aggressive approach to the SB category requires keeping a close eye on **Daulton Varsho** (51.83) and **Jeremiah Jackson** (55.67). **Daulton Varsho** faces a tough test in Yamamoto, and his score is dragged down by the catcher's elite pop-time, which necessitates a more cautious approach on the basepaths. Conversely, **Jeremiah Jackson** remains a priority start; his ability to exploit a slower SP delivery keeps him firmly in the outfield mix. The most difficult bench decision involved **Matt Chapman** (41.60), who narrowly missed the cut. While the wind at his home park offered a slight boost, the combination of a tough matchup against S\u00e1nchez and his diminishing efficiency relative to our starters made him an easy exclusion to preserve our daily games cap.\n\nRisk management is a key focus today, specifically regarding the high-end opposition. **Cal Raleigh** (46.76) and **Brendan Donovan** (51.17) are navigating dangerous waters against Eovaldi. While **Brendan Donovan** is propped up by his lead-off role, both players see their scores suppressed by Eovaldi\u2019s elite skill profile. We are also monitoring **Geraldo Perdomo** (49.01) and **Gleyber Torres** (52.28); neither has an ideal matchup, and any shift in the wind or a late-inning defensive replacement could drag their efficiency below the 40-point threshold. We will hold firm with these starters for now, but keep **Jung Hoo Lee**, **Wenceel Perez**, and **Drew Gilbert** on high alert if early-game defensive switches occur.",
